secureboot-watchdog (0.6) noble; urgency=medium

  * Replace the bash/zenity post-notification flow with a native GTK4 +
    libadwaita 1.5 application written in Rust (gtk4-rs 0.9, libadwaita-rs
    0.7). Native libnotify notifications still come from
    bin/secureboot-notify; clicking an action now opens the new app
    (/usr/bin/secureboot-watchdog-ui) instead of zenity dialogs.
  * The new app drives the 8-screen mockup via an AdwNavigationView:
    overview -> details (info-only) or fix-flow (5-page Stack of
    confirm/password/progress/success/failure). Steps in the progress
    view come from [STEPS]/[STEP] markers now emitted by secureboot-fix
    in each fix_* handler. LUKS passphrase / new MOK password are
    collected via AdwPasswordEntryRow and piped to pkexec on stdin.
  * Slim bin/secureboot-notify from ~115 lines to ~50: keep the
    watcher + dedup hash + notify-send, drop the zenity flows.
  * debian/control: drop zenity; add GTK4/libadwaita runtime depends;
    add Rust/GTK build depends. Architecture: all -> any (the Rust
    binary is amd64-specific now).
  * Devbox: rustc, cargo, clippy, rustfmt, pkg-config, glib,
    blueprint-compiler, gtk4.dev/libadwaita.dev/pango.dev/cairo.dev/
    gdk-pixbuf.dev/graphene.dev/harfbuzz.dev. (.dev suffix per
    jetify-com/devbox#2761.) debhelper + lintian still come from apt.

 -- Gitii <Gitii@users.noreply.github.com>  Wed, 17 Jun 2026 12:30:00 +0000

secureboot-watchdog (0.5) noble; urgency=medium

  * check_tpm_pcr_drift: query the system journal, not the kernel-only
    journal. The previous implementation used JOURNAL_CMD which defaults
    to `journalctl -kb` — kernel messages only — so the widened regex
    added in 0.4 still missed the systemd-cryptsetup userspace lines
    ("Failed to unseal secret using TPM2"). Split out SYSTEM_JOURNAL_CMD
    (without -k) and use it for TPM/cryptsetup checks.

 -- Gitii <Gitii@users.noreply.github.com>  Wed, 17 Jun 2026 11:00:00 +0000

secureboot-watchdog (0.4) noble; urgency=medium

  * check_tpm_pcr_drift: widen the journal regex to also match
    "Failed to unseal secret using TPM2" (the actual message systemd-
    cryptsetup logs on PCR mismatch or TPM lockout) and "tpm2.*lockout".
    The previous regex only matched a message systemd doesn't actually
    emit, so PCR drift went undetected even when boot unlock failed.
  * Make TPM_PCR_DRIFT auto-fixable: secureboot-fix now re-seals the
    LUKS keyslot against the current PCRs (7+11 by default, overridable
    via TPM2_PCRS env var). It reads the LUKS passphrase from stdin
    (the user notifier collects it via zenity --password before pkexec)
    and best-effort clears any TPM dictionary-attack lockout via
    tpm2_dictionarylockout first.
  * Add tpm2-tools as a Recommends so the DA-lockout reset is available
    by default.
  * secureboot-notify: distinguish between two secret kinds — fresh MOK
    enrollment password (asked twice) vs existing LUKS passphrase (asked
    once) — and label the zenity dialogs accordingly.

 -- Gitii <Gitii@users.noreply.github.com>  Wed, 17 Jun 2026 10:50:00 +0000

secureboot-watchdog (0.3) noble; urgency=medium

  * check_mok_enrollment: fix false-positive MOK_NOT_ENROLLED. The check
    was computing the SHA-256 fingerprint of each MOK .der and searching
    for it in the `mokutil --list-enrolled` output, but mokutil on noble
    only prints SHA-1 fingerprints — so the check always failed. Now
    compute both SHA-1 and SHA-256 and match either.

 -- Gitii <Gitii@users.noreply.github.com>  Wed, 17 Jun 2026 10:30:00 +0000

secureboot-watchdog (0.2) noble; urgency=medium

  * secureboot-monitor.service: set RuntimeDirectoryPreserve=yes so
    /run/secureboot-monitor/status.json survives the oneshot's exit.
    Previously the directory was wiped as soon as the service finished,
    leaving the user notifier nothing to read.

